english:
  title: Preface to Poems Sent Off to Wu Fengxiao, Inspector of Document Preservation at Zhongzhou
  author: Yun Huae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Wu Zhifu of Daning, the Grand Historiographer, learned in the hall of Yangcun and came forth from the gate of Yuin—a student of the sages. First among the examination laureates, finest of the literati, distinguished in the garden of letters. Born to nobility, he stood apart from his peers even as a student, rising with honor to the highest rank, entering the imperial academy to stand among the worthy, attending closely upon the throne. His words rang true, his brush was righteous—in both he had nothing of which to be ashamed. I have companioned with him for more than a dozen years, and our friendship has been most intimate, our understanding most profound. His learning is broad, his talent quick; his speech is refined, his spirit harmonious. He honors his parents, keeps faith with friends, is diligent in his duties, and careful in his dealings with all. Truly, he is a man of state in these times, a worthy of all under heaven.

    In the sixth month of the jiashen year of Yongle, heeding imperial command, he departed to air the historical records at Zhongzhou—following ancient precedent. As he prepared to leave, the gentlemen of the archives sent him off with poems and asked me to write this preface.

    I have heard it said that in ages past, the great historiographer traveled throughout all lands, gathering texts from stone chambers and golden repositories, composing the Records of History in one hundred thirty chapters—majestic and vigorous, sweeping and wondrous. Later chroniclers could not exceed his bounds. Surely this was the talent of a great historian. Yet, regrettably, his learning was mixed and impure; measured against the Way, it fell short. Scholars could not help but feel some regret.

    Now Zhifu encounters enlightened rule and serves in the Office of History. He illuminates the learning of the Spring and Autumn Annals, grasping the subtle meanings of the sages, while gathering the remaining texts of the stone chambers and uncovering the secret records of former ages. Thus widening his knowledge and unleashing his talents, what he shall achieve will surely transcend mere majesty and vigor, sweeping scope and wondrous originality.

    Zhifu must endeavor ever more! As for the pleasures of mountains and waters, the sight of flourishing cities and their beauty—these may delight the eye and stir the heart, but they are but trifles. Why should such things be spoken of in regard to Zhifu?
  footnotes:
    - Yangcun and Yuin likely refer to the schools or teachers under whom Wu studied, possibly referencing specific literati or philosophical traditions.
    - The 'stone chambers and golden repositories' (石室金匱) refer to imperial archives where official histories and state records were preserved.
    - The 'Records of History' (史記) by Sima Qian is one of the most influential works of Chinese historiography.
    - The 'Spring and Autumn Annals' (春秋) is a foundational Confucian text traditionally attributed to Confucius, used for studying moral philosophy and statecraft.
